.TH ssh_sftp 3 "ssh 5.5.1" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
ssh_sftp \- SFTP client.

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
This module implements an SSH FTP (SFTP) client. SFTP is a secure, encrypted file transfer service available for SSH.

.SH DATA TYPES
.LP
.B
\fBchunk_size() :: undefined | pos_integer().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_fun() ::\fR
\fB          fun((TextIn :: binary(), crypto_state()) -> crypto_result()).\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_result() ::\fR
\fB          {ok, TextOut :: binary(), crypto_state()} |\fR
\fB          {ok, TextOut :: binary(), crypto_state(), chunk_size()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The initial \fIcrypto_state/0\fR returned from the \fIinit_fun/0\fR is folded into repeated applications of the \fIcrypto_fun/0\fR in the tar_crypto_spec. The binary returned from that fun is sent to the remote SFTP server and the new \fIcrypto_state/0\fR is used in the next call of the \fIcrypto_fun/0\fR.

.PP
If the \fIcrypto_fun/0\fR reurns a \fIchunk_size/0\fR, that value is as block size for further blocks in calls to \fIcrypto_fun/0\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBcrypto_state() :: any().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
The \fIinit_fun/0\fR in the tar_crypto_spec is applied once prior to any other \fIcrypto\fR operation. The intention is that this function initiates the encryption or decryption for example by calling \fIcrypto:crypto_init/4\fR or similar. The \fIcrypto_state/0\fR is the state such a function may return.

.PP
If the selected cipher needs to have the input data partitioned into blocks of a certain size, the \fIinit_fun/0\fR should return the second form of return value with the \fIchunk_size/0\fR set to the block size. If the \fIchunk_size/0\fR is \fIundefined\fR, the size of the \fIPlainBin\fRs varies, because this is intended for stream crypto, whereas a fixed \fIchunk_size/0\fR is intended for block crypto. A \fIchunk_size/0\fR can be changed in the return from the \fIcrypto_fun/0\fR. The value can be changed between \fIpos_integer/0\fR and \fIundefined\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBdecrypt_spec() :: {init_fun(), crypto_fun()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Specifies the encryption or decryption applied to tar files when using \fIopen_tar/3\fR or \fIopen_tar/4\fR.

.PP
The encryption or decryption is applied to the generated stream of bytes prior to sending the resulting stream to the SFTP server.

.PP
For code examples see Section Example with encryption in the ssh Users Guide.


.RE
.B
\fBencrypt_spec() :: {init_fun(), crypto_fun(), final_fun()}.\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBfinal_fun() ::\fR
\fB          fun((FinalTextIn :: binary(), crypto_state()) ->\fR
\fB                  {ok, FinalTextOut :: binary()}).\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
If doing encryption, the \fIfinal_fun/0\fR in the tar_crypto_spec is applied to the last piece of data. The \fIfinal_fun/0\fR is responsible for padding (if needed) and encryption of that last piece.


.RE
.B
\fBinit_fun() ::\fR
\fB          fun(() -> {ok, crypto_state()}) |\fR
\fB          fun(() -> {ok, crypto_state(), chunk_size()}).\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
.B
\fBreason() :: atom() | string() | tuple().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
A description of the reason why an operation failed.

.PP
The \fIatom/0\fR value is formed from the sftp error codes in the protocol-level responses as defined in draft-ietf-secsh-filexfer-13 section 9.1. The codes are named as \fISSH_FX_*\fR which are transformed into lowercase of the star-part. E.g. the error code \fISSH_FX_NO_SUCH_FILE\fR will cause the \fIreason/0\fR to be \fIno_such_file\fR.

.PP
The \fIstring/0\fR reason is the error information from the server in case of an exit-signal. If that information is empty, the reason is the exit signal name.

.PP
The \fItuple/0\fR reason are other errors like for example \fI{exit_status,1}\fR.


.RE
.B
\fBsftp_option() ::\fR
\fB          {timeout, timeout()} |\fR
\fB          {sftp_vsn, pos_integer()} |\fR
\fB          {window_size, pos_integer()} |\fR
\fB          {packet_size, pos_integer()}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Specifies available SFTP options.


.RE
.B
\fBtar_crypto_spec() :: encrypt_spec() | decrypt_spec().\fR

.br
.RS

.RE
